We can start by using L'Hopital's rule on the given limit:
\begin{align*}
\lim_{x \rightarrow 2} \frac{f(x)g(x)}{f'(x)g'(x)} &= \lim_{x \rightarrow 2} \frac{f(x)g(x)}{f'(x)g'(x)} \cdot \frac{f''(x)g'(x)}{f''(x)g'(x)} \\
&= \lim_{x \rightarrow 2} \frac{f(x)f''(x)g(x)}{(f'(x))^2(g'(x))^2 + f'(x)f''(x)g(x)g'(x)} \\
&= \lim_{x \rightarrow 2} \frac{f(x)f''(x)g(x)}{(f'(x))^2(g'(x))^2} \cdot \frac{1}{1 + \frac{f'(x)f''(x)g(x)g'(x)}{(f'(x))^2(g'(x))^2}} \\
&= \lim_{x \rightarrow 2} \frac{f(x)f''(x)g(x)}{(f'(x))^2(g'(x))^2} \cdot \frac{1}{1 + \frac{f'(x)}{g'(x)} \cdot \frac{f''(x)}{g''(x)} \cdot \frac{g(x)}{f(x)}}
\end{align*}
Since the limit is equal to 1, we have:
\begin{align*}
\lim_{x \rightarrow 2} \frac{f(x)f''(x)g(x)}{(f'(x))^2(g'(x))^2} &= 1 \\
\Rightarrow \lim_{x \rightarrow 2} \frac{f''(x)}{(f'(x))^2} \cdot \frac{g(x)}{(g'(x))^2} &= \frac{1}{f(2)} \cdot \frac{1}{g(2)} \\
\Rightarrow f''(2) \cdot (g'(2))^2 &= (f'(2))^2 \cdot g(2)
\end{align*}
Since $f'(2) = g(2) = 0$, we have $f''(2) \cdot (g'(2))^2 = 0$. But $g'(2) \neq 0$, so we must have $f''(2) = 0$.

Therefore, the answer is $\boxed{\textbf{(B) }f \text{ has a local maximum at } x=2}$.
